Red Wine Quality Analysis by Payam Gerami

This data set contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

Univariate Plots Section

Quality

We can see in the following diagrams that the quality distribution is fairly normal and we do not have sgnificant outliers.

# exploring the quality distribution
p1 <- ggplot( aes( x = quality), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram()
p2 <- ggplot( aes( x = quality), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram() +
  scale_x_log10()
p3 <- ggplot( aes( x = 1, y = quality), data = wine) +
  geom_boxplot()
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,ncol = 3)

In the following section we explore other variables that have an effect on the quality.

Volatile Acidity

# exploring the volatile.acidity distribution
p1 <- ggplot( aes( x = volatile.acidity), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram()
p2 <- ggplot( aes( x = volatile.acidity), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram() +
  xlim(0.15,0.95)
p3 <- ggplot( aes( x = 1, y = volatile.acidity), data = wine) +
  geom_boxplot()
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,ncol = 3)

The amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste. As we can see there are some outliers that we can check later to see the quality of the wine with such a high level of acetic acid.

Citric Acid

# exploring the citric.acid distribution
p1 <- ggplot( aes( x = citric.acid), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram()
p2 <- ggplot( aes( x = citric.acid), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram() +
  scale_x_log10()
p3 <- ggplot( aes( x = 1, y = citric.acid), data = wine) +
  geom_boxplot()
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,ncol = 3)

Found in small quantities, citric acid can add freshness and flavor to wines.

Residual Sugar

# exploring the residual.sugar distribution
p1 <- ggplot( aes( x = residual.sugar), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram()
p2 <- ggplot( aes( x = residual.sugar), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram() +
  xlim(1,4)
p3 <- ggplot( aes( x = 1, y = residual.sugar), data = wine) +
  geom_boxplot()
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,ncol = 3)

The amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, its rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet. The maximum amount of sugar we have in our dataset is 15.5 grams but majarity of wines in our sample have between 1 and 4 grams of sugar and the distribution is right skewed.

Total Sulfur Dioxide

# exploring the total.sulfur.dioxide distribution
p1 <- ggplot( aes( x = total.sulfur.dioxide), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram()
p2 <- ggplot( aes( x = total.sulfur.dioxide), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=50)
p3 <- ggplot( aes( x = 1, y = total.sulfur.dioxide), data = wine) +
  geom_boxplot()
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,ncol = 3)

Amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine. As we can see here we have a couple of outliers as well which we can check later to find out the possible effect they have a the quality.

PH

# exploring the pH distribution
p1 <- ggplot( aes( x = pH), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram()
p2 <- ggplot( aes( x = pH), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram() +
  scale_x_log10()
p3 <- ggplot( aes( x = 1, y = pH), data = wine) +
  geom_boxplot()
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,ncol = 3)

Describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale. The distribution is almost normal and most of the values are in the expected range.

Alcohol

# exploring the alcohol distribution
p1 <- ggplot( aes( x = alcohol), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram()
p2 <- ggplot( aes( x = alcohol), data = wine) +
  geom_histogram() +
  scale_x_log10()
p3 <- ggplot( aes( x = 1, y = alcohol), data = wine) +
  geom_boxplot()
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3,ncol = 3)

The percent alcohol content of the wine. Here we might have only one type of wine with too much alcohol in it.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1,599 wines in the dataset with 11 features (fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol ).

Other observations:

  • The quality is an integer number with 6 values.
  • Sugar content distribution is interesting and it shows that most of the wines have between 1 and 4 gram/liter but there are several other wines that have more than 4 grams which is not necessarly a bad thing.
  • As stated in the dataset description, it seems that diffrent types of acid have significant impact on the quality.
  • 75% of the wines have less than 11.10% alcohol

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Since the quality has only 6 values, we categorize this variable into the following factor:

  • < 3 very bad
  • 4 bad
  • 5 average
  • 6 good
  • 7 excelent
  • > 8 very excelent
wine$quality.bucket <- cut(wine$quality, 
                       breaks = c(0, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8), 
                       labels = c('very bad','bad','average','good','excelent',
                                  'very excelent'))
